COLIN
-----

This package contains COLIN, a planner for domains with continuous numeric
and/or duration dependent effects.  For more details, see the papers:

"COLIN: Planning with Continuous Linear Numeric Change", A. J. Coles,
A. I. Coles, M. Fox and D. Long, JAIR, 2012

"Temporal Planning in Domains with Linear Processes", A. J. Coles,
A. I. Coles, M. Fox and D. Long, IJCAI, 2009

Build Prerequisites
-------------------

In order to function, COLIN requires either CLP or CPLEX.  CLP is generally
faster, but CPLEX is also supported.  In both cases, you also need:

- cmake (3.10 or newer)
- perl, bison and flex (used to build the parser)


Compiling on Ubuntu 24.04 (recommended)
----------------------------------------

1) Install dependencies:

sudo apt-get install build-essential cmake \
                     coinor-libclp-dev coinor-libcbc-dev \
                     coinor-libcoinutils-dev coinor-libosi-dev \
                     coinor-libcgl-dev \
                     libbz2-dev bison flex perl

2) Create a build directory and compile:

mkdir -p build
cd build
cmake ../src

cmake --build . --target colin -j$(nproc) && make 

or 

cmake --build . -j$(nproc)



This produces two binaries inside the build directory:

  build/colin/colin-planner   — the COLIN planning binary
  build/VALfiles/parser       — the VAL PDDL parser/validator


Compiling (legacy scripts)
--------------------------

The repository also contains scripts for older configurations:

run-cmake-debug           — CLP backend, debugging enabled
run-cmake-release         — CLP backend, optimised non-static binary
run-cmake-static          — CLP backend, statically linked binary
run-cmake-for-cplex-debug-x86    — CLP/CPLEX backend, debug (32-bit CPLEX)
run-cmake-for-cplex-static-x86   — CLP/CPLEX backend, static (32-bit CPLEX)

After running one of these scripts, build with the matching script:

./build-debug     (after run-cmake-debug)
./build-release   (after run-cmake-release)
./build-static    (after run-cmake-static or run-cmake-for-cplex-static-x86)

Note: static builds require static CLP libraries.  If the packaged
coinor-* libraries are shared-only, you may need to build CBC from
source with static libraries enabled.


Documentation (Doxygen + UML)
-----------------------------

A complete Doxygen configuration is provided at:

Doxyfile

It is configured with Graphviz/dot and UML-style diagrams enabled
(`HAVE_DOT = YES`, `UML_LOOK = YES`, call graphs, caller graphs,
include graphs, directory graphs, and class/collaboration graphs).

1) Install documentation dependencies on Ubuntu 24.04:

sudo apt-get install doxygen graphviz

2) Generate documentation from the repository root:

doxygen Doxyfile

Generated outputs:

- docs/html/index.html   (main browsable documentation)
- docs/xml/              (machine-readable XML output)
- docs/latex/            (LaTeX sources)


Running
-------

PDDL examples are grouped in:

examples/pddl/

Files included:

- test-domain.pddl + test-problem.pddl (small Blocks World validation example)
- Domain_1.pddl + Problem_1.pddl
- Domain_2.pddl + Problem_2.pddl
- Domain_3.pddl + Problem_3.pddl

Run the planner on the small validation example:

./build/colin/colin-planner examples/pddl/test-domain.pddl examples/pddl/test-problem.pddl

Validate syntax with the VAL parser:

./build/VALfiles/parser examples/pddl/test-domain.pddl examples/pddl/test-problem.pddl

Run the planner on another example pair:

./build/colin/colin-planner examples/pddl/Domain_1.pddl examples/pddl/Problem_1.pddl

The planner does not enforce time or memory limits by itself.  For example,
to limit it to 30 minutes of CPU and 4GiB of memory:

ulimit -t 1800
ulimit -v 4000000
./build/colin/colin-planner examples/pddl/test-domain.pddl examples/pddl/test-problem.pddl


Feedback
--------

If you do something exciting with COLIN, do let us know.  If you tried to do 
something with it, but it failed, you may have found a bug.  In common with
POPF, the three most likely sources of bugs are:

The three most common causes of bugs (over 90% of bug reports) are:

- Using ADL. ADL is supported in the conditions of preferences, in the
  time-dependent costs of goal-collection actions, and one or two other niche
  cases.  We've attempted to make the planner degrade gracefully, but there are
  still cases where it will report problems using ADL as being unsolvable.
  Check there are no negative preconditions in your domain.
  
- Domain modelling bugs. COLIN and POPF support the full start--end semantics
  of PDDL 2.1, and self-overlapping actions, so errors in the temporal
  placement of preconditions and effects (at start, at end etc.) are more
  likely to cause issues with POPF than with other planners. For instance, if
  a 'move' action is written (erroneously) as deleting the old location at the
  end (rather than at the start), then POPF will consider concurrent move 
  actions for the same vehicle; whereas planners which do not make as clear a 
  distinction between the start and end-points of durative actions would not 
  consider this. Thus, in domains with errors such as this, POPF might have to
  consider a far larger search space than other temporal planners.

- If the plans don't validate, ensure you are passing the '-t 0.001' flag to
  VAL: the planner uses an epsilon value of 0.001, smaller than the default
  0.01 value used in VAL.

If none of those apply, email as small a possible domain and problem file
that cause the error you're observing to Andrew Coles:
firstname.lastname@kcl.ac.uk


